qx|P2,The Opener's Response to NMF |HT|d|cs|1|cp|4|fp||at|
^-{ The Opener's Response to NMF }
^-|CP||AT|^b@2^z@3We learn of the following information when NMF auction begins. Opener generally has 12-14/a bad 15 points (a minimum opening hand) and does not have a five-card major because he did not open one of a major. Further, assuming the partnership plays strong NT, he does not have  a balanced 15-17 point hand. For now, let us keep the 2NT bid aside. Moreover, opener does not have four-card support for the major bid by the responder. Hearing a NMF bid from responder, opener's obligation is to further explain his hand's |CP|8|AT|SHAPE |CP||AT|and |CP|8|AT|STRENGTH. |CP||
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


AT|

Responder should not bid NMF unless he has invitational or game values--at least 10 high card points or more. Even a responder who is a passed hand must hold a minimum of 9+ points in order to bid NMF. As usual, the point ranges given by different experts are not the same. Personally, I like to use Bergen's counting technique and consider any hand with 10+ Starting Points suitable for NMF bid--passed hand or not.|
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


AT|

What if the responder's hand has less than an invitational values? Generally, with fewer points the responder should pass the 1 No-Trump rebid or, with support, raise the first suit of the opener. Regardless, the responder's hand should be at least strong enough to bid at the two level or to be in game either in No-Trump or one of the majors.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


AT|

Armed with that information, let us consider what the available second rebids are for the opener playing NMF. First, opener should re-evaluate his hand's strength and determine whether the hand's value is "minimum" (12 to poor 13) or "maximum" (good 13 to 14). Strength determines the level and the shape determines the type of his bid. Again, let me repeat that the opener does not have four-card support for the bid major. If he did he would have raised the suit and not bid 1NT.|
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


AT|

Opener's first obligation is to show 3-card support for the major bid. Therefore, holding 3-card support, he bids the major at the two level with "minimum opening hand" and at the three level with a "maximum opening hand." If he does not have such support, he bids 2NT with a minimum or 3NT with maximum hand.  Some experts recommend using 2@D instead of 2NT so the partnership can explore further and avoid a possible bad 3NT auction. The first priority, however, is to show support for the responder's major. Let us look at some examples. You see only the opener's hand.|
