ht|m|Va|4|at|^b@2^z@3Generally, when responder bids 1@S and then bids NMF he |FP|2|AT|always |FP||AT|has five spades or more and may also have four hearts. For that reason, playing NMF in this situation, opener's first priority is to show his 4-heart suit if any. Not having a 4-card heart suit, the next priority is to show a 3-card spade suit. Holding neither, he should bid NT. The level of each rebid correlates with the value of the hand. In this situation the priority clearly is given to showing the 4-card heart suit. |
PG| ***** 69 ***** |


AT|

By doing so, the partnership doesn't miss a 4-4 heart fit which is preferable to a 5-3 spade fit. Moreover, the bidding stays low and allows the partnership to explore further. The rest is similar to when responder bids one heart. The following are opener's next rebid options in the above auctions in order of their priority.   |
PG| ***** 70 ***** |


FP|2|AT|
    
A 2@H by opener   = Promising four hearts with minimum strength, and may have three spades.  |
PG| ***** 71 ***** |


AT|
A 3@H by opener   = Promising four hearts with maximum strength, and  may have three spades. |
PG| ***** 72 ***** |


AT|
A 2@S by opener   = Promising three spades with minimum strength  and denies four hearts |
PG| ***** 73 ***** |


AT|
A 3@S by opener   = Promising three spades with maximum strength and  denies four hearts.  |
PG| ***** 74 ***** |


AT|
A 2NT by opener = Promising a minimum strength and denies four hearts and three spades. |
PG| ***** 75 ***** |


AT| 
A 3NT by opener = Promising maximum strength and denies four hearts and three spades. |
PG| ***** 76 ***** |


